# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cert-manager
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The **Automatic Certificate Management Environment** (**ACME**) protocol is a communications protocol for automating interactions between certificate authorities and their users' servers, allowing the automated deployment of public key infrastructure at very low cost.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] It was designed by the Internet Security Research Group (ISRG) for their Let's Encrypt service.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The protocol, based on passing JSON-formatted messages over HTTPS, has been published as an Internet Standard in RFC 8555 by its own chartered IETF working group.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] An automated certificate management protocol was being developed simultaneously by a team led by Alex Halderman at the University of Michigan and by Peter Eckersley at the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), and another team at Mozilla Corporation led by Josh Aas and Eric Rescorla.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Upon learning of each other's existence, the two teams joined to create the Internet Security Research Group (ISRG) in May 2013, a public-benefit non-profit corporation, of which Aas became director.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ISRG continued to develop the ACME protocol for use in their Let's Encrypt certificate authority (CA), with the goal of creating a free, open, secure and private internet, as well as their CA softwares Boulder and Certbot.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The aims of the ACME protocol were to lower the cost of publicly trusted TLS certificates and eliminate the complexity and error-prone nature of installing new certificates.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] A 2013 study co-authored by Halderman found that, on the internet, only 45% of TLS certificates were correctly configured, and about 20% failed to be replaced before their expiration.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The Let's Encrypt certificate authority, the first to support ACME, was opened to the public in December 2015 using the still proprietary protocol referred to as 'ACMEv1'.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] This version was given for public standardization to a newly created ACME working group of the Internet Engineering Task Force under the Internet Society in February 2015.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ACME protocol continues to receive published extensions into 2026.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ACME protocol functions from the server (CA) point of view by assigning to each client an ACME account, bound to a URI on the server.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] An account is created by the client querying the server's directory URI, after which the server responds with additional informational endpoints along with the CA's terms of service agreement.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] An ACME account is created after the client agrees to the terms by setting the relevant reply field to true.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The client then obtains pre-authorization from the server, ensuring the forthcoming certificate will meet the server's requirements, by sending a subset of the certificate's fields.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The server then replies with an 'order object' URL.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] This packet contains a list of authorization methods supported by the server which ensure the client is in possession of the subject of the potential certificate.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The client downloads an authorization token from the URL(s) indicated in the response and makes this token available, e.g. by creating a DNS record containing it or opening an HTTP endpoint responding with it.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] After the authorization token has been made available at the address of the desired certificate's subject, the client notifies the server that it is prepared for validation which is carried out by the server in accessing the authorization token.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Once the authorization is complete the client sends a certificate signing request (RFC 2986) which contains the certificate to be signed, resulting in an updated order object containing the decision of the CA.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] If the request was valid, the CA has signed the client's certificate and the client may download it at the returned URL.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Functionality also exists for certificate revocation, account deletion, and other forms of authentication.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] The ISRG provides free and open-source reference implementations for ACME: certbot is a Python-based implementation of server certificate management software using the ACME protocol, and *boulder* is a certificate authority implementation, written in Go.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Client implementations are available for Rust in the `acme-client` and `instant_acme` crates.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Since 2015 a large variety of client options have appeared for all operating systems.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Web servers like Caddy, Traefik Proxy, Nginx (starting in August, 2025), and Apache HTTP Server (2.4.30 and later) have built in support for automatically acquiring a TLS certificate using the ACME protocol.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] API v1 specification was published on April 12, 2016.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] It supports issuing certificates for fully-qualified domain names, such as `example.com` or `cluster.example.com`, but not wildcards like `*.example.com`.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Let's Encrypt turned off API v1 support on 1 June 2021.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] API v2 was released March 13, 2018 after being pushed back several times.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] ACME v2 is not backwards compatible with v1.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] Version 2 supports wildcard domains, such as `*.example.com`, allowing for many subdomains to have trusted TLS, e.g.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] `https://cluster01.example.com`, `https://cluster02.example.com`, `https://example.com`, on private networks under a single domain using a single shared "wildcard" certificate.
[src:cert-manager/automatic-certificate-management-environment] A major new requirement in v2 is that requests for wildcard certificates require the modification of a Domain Name Service TXT record, verifying control over the domain.
[src:cert-manager/installation] Learn about the various ways you can install cert-manager and how to choose between them.
[src:cert-manager/installation] 📖 Read more about installing cert-manager using kubectl apply and static manifests.
[src:cert-manager/installation] 📖 **kubectl apply**: For new users we recommend installing cert-manager using kubectl apply and static manifests.
[src:cert-manager/installation] 📖 **helm**: You can use helm to install cert-manager and this also allows you to customize the installation if necessary.
[src:cert-manager/installation] 🚧 **cmctl**: Try the experimental `cmctl x install` command to quickly install cert-manager.
[src:cert-manager/installation] 📖 **Continuous Deployment**: Learn how to automate the installation of cert-manager using tools like Flux and Argo CD.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The mission of the organization is to create a more secure and privacy-respecting World Wide Web by promoting the widespread adoption of HTTPS.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt certificates are valid for 90 days by default, during which renewal can take place at any time.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Optionally, certificates can be issued which are valid for 45 days (tlsserver profile) and 6 days (shortlived profile).
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] This is handled by an automated process designed to overcome manual creation, validation, signing, installation, and renewal of certificates for secure websites.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The project claims its goal is to make encrypted connections to World Wide Web servers ubiquitous.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] By eliminating payment, web server configuration, validation email management and certificate renewal tasks, it is meant to significantly lower the complexity of setting up and maintaining TLS encryption.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On a Linux web server, execution of only two commands is sufficient to set up HTTPS encryption and acquire and install certificates.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] To that end, a software package was included into the official Debian and Ubuntu software repositories.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Current initiatives of major browser developers such as Mozilla and Google to deprecate unencrypted HTTP are counting on the availability of Let's Encrypt.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The project is acknowledged to have the potential to accomplish encrypted connections as the default case for the entire Web.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The service only issues domain-validated certificates, since they can be fully automated.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Organization Validation and Extended Validation Certificates both require human validation of any registrants, and are therefore not offered by Let's Encrypt.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Support of ACME v2 and wildcard certificates was added in March 2018.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The domain validation (DV) utilized by Let's Encrypt dates back to 2002 and was at first controversial when introduced by GeoTrust before becoming a widely accepted method for the issuance of SSL certificates.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] By being as transparent as possible, the organization hopes to both protect its own trustworthiness and guard against attacks and manipulation attempts.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] For that purpose it regularly publishes transparency reports, publicly logs all ACME transactions (e.g. by using Certificate Transparency), and uses open standards and free software as much as possible.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The Let's Encrypt project was started in 2012 by two Mozilla employees, Josh Aas and Eric Rescorla, together with Peter Eckersley at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and J.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Alex Halderman at the University of Michigan.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Internet Security Research Group, the company behind Let's Encrypt, was incorporated in May 2013.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt was announced publicly on November 18, 2014.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On January 28, 2015, the ACME protocol was officially submitted to the IETF for standardization.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On April 9, 2015, the ISRG and the Linux Foundation declared their collaboration.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The root and intermediate certificates were generated in the beginning of June.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On June 16, 2015, the final launch schedule for the service was announced, with the first certificate expected to be issued sometime in the week of July 27, 2015, followed by a limited issuance period to test security and scalability.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] General availability of the service was originally planned to begin sometime in the week of September 14, 2015.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On August 7, 2015, the launch schedule was amended to provide more time for ensuring system security and stability, with the first certificate to be issued in the week of September 7, 2015 followed by general availability in the week of November 16, 2015.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On September 14, 2015, Let's Encrypt issued its first certificate, which was for the domain helloworld.letsencrypt.org.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On the same day, ISRG submitted its root program applications to Mozilla, Microsoft, Google and Apple.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On October 19, 2015, the intermediate certificates became cross-signed by IdenTrust, causing all certificates issued by Let's Encrypt to be trusted by all major browsers.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On November 12, 2015, Let's Encrypt announced that general availability would be pushed back and that the first public beta would commence on December 3, 2015.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The public beta ran from December 3, 2015 to April 12, 2016.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On March 3, 2020, Let's Encrypt announced that it would have to revoke over 3 million certificates on March 4, due to a flaw in its Certificate Authority software.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Through working with software vendors and contacting site operators, Let's Encrypt was able to get 1.7 million of the affected certificates renewed before the deadline.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] They ultimately decided not to revoke the remaining affected certificates, as the security risk was low and the certificates were to expire within the next 90 days.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The mass-revocation event has significantly increased the global revocation rate.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] In March 2020, Let's Encrypt was awarded the Free Software Foundation's annual Award for Projects of Social Benefit.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On February 27, 2020, Let's Encrypt announced having issued a billion certificates.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] In April 2022, Let's Encrypt was awarded the Levchin Prize for “fundamental improvements to the certificate ecosystem that provide free certificates for all”.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] As of 2025, Let's Encrypt serves more than 700 million websites worldwide, making it the largest certificate authority in the world.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] In January 2025, Let's Encrypt announced the retirement of its free email expiry notifications and recommended Red Sift Certificates Lite as its certificate monitoring service.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] In June 2015, Let's Encrypt announced the generation of their first RSA root certificate, ISRG Root X1.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The root certificate was used to sign two intermediate certificates, which are also cross-signed by the certificate authority IdenTrust.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] One of the intermediate certificates is used to sign issued certificates, while the other is kept offline as a backup in case of problems with the first intermediate certificate.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Because the IdenTrust certificate was already widely trusted by major web browsers, Let's Encrypt certificates can normally be validated and accepted by relying parties even before browser vendors include the ISRG root certificate as a trust anchor.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt developers planned to generate an ECDSA root key back in 2015, but then pushed back the plan to early 2016, then to 2019, and finally to 2020.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] On September 3, 2020, Let's Encrypt issued six new certificates: one new ECDSA root named "ISRG Root X2", four intermediates, and one cross-sign.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The new ISRG Root X2 is cross-signed with ISRG Root X1, Let's Encrypt's own root certificate.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt did not issue an OCSP responder for the new intermediate certificates and instead plans to rely solely on certificate revocation lists (CRLs) to recall compromised certificates and short validity periods to reduce danger of certificate compromise.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The challenge–response protocol used to automate enrolling with the certificate authority is called Automatic Certificate Management Environment (ACME).
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] It can query either Web servers or DNS servers controlled by the domain covered by the certificate to be issued.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Based on whether the resulting responses match the expectations, control of the enrollee over the domain is assured (domain validation).
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The ACME client software can set up a dedicated TLS server that gets queried by the ACME certificate authority server with requests using Server Name Indication (Domain Validation using Server Name Indication, DVSNI), or it can use hooks to publish responses to existing Web and DNS servers.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The validation processes are run multiple times over separate network paths.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Checking whether DNS entries are provisioned is done from multiple geographically diverse locations to make DNS spoofing attacks harder to carry out.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] ACME interactions are based on exchanging JSON documents over HTTPS connections.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The specification developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) is a proposed standard, RFC 8555.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Prior to the completion and publication of RFC 8555, Let's Encrypt implemented a pre-standard draft of the ACME protocol.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] RFC 8555 introduced breaking changes and as such it has been dubbed ACMEv2.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt implemented the new version and started pushing existing clients into upgrades.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The nudging was implemented with intermittent down-times of the ACMEv1 API.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The end-of-lifetime was announced with dates and phases in "End of Life Plan for ACMEv1".
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Since November 8, 2019, ACMEv1 no longer accepts new account registrations.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Since June 2020, ACMEv1 stopped accepting new domain validations.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] From January 2021, ACMEv1 underwent 24-hour brownouts.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The ACMEv1 API was turned off completely on June 1, 2021.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The certificate authority consists of a piece of software called Boulder, written in Go, that implements the server side of the ACME protocol.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] It is published as free software with source code under the terms of version 2 of the Mozilla Public License (MPL).
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] It provides a RESTful API that can be accessed over a TLS-encrypted channel.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] An Apache-licensed Python certificate management program called *certbot* (formerly *letsencrypt*) gets installed on the client side (the Web server of an enrollee).
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] This is used to order the certificate, to conduct the domain validation process, to install the certificate, to configure the HTTPS encryption in the HTTP server, and later to regularly renew the certificate.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] After installation and agreeing to the user license, executing a single command is enough to get a valid certificate installed.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Additional options like OCSP stapling or HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) can also be enabled.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Automatic setup initially only works with Apache and nginx.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Let's Encrypt issues certificates valid for 90 days.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] The reason given is that these certificates "limit damage from key compromise and mis-issuance" and encourage automation.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] Initially, Let's Encrypt developed its own ACME client – Certbot – as an official implementation.
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] This has been transferred to Electronic Frontier Foundation and its name "letsencrypt" has been changed to "certbot".
[src:cert-manager/let-s-encrypt] There is a large selection of ACME clients and projects for a number of environments developed by the community.
[src:cert-manager/page] cert-manager creates TLS certificates for workloads in your Kubernetes or OpenShift cluster and renews the certificates before they expire.
[src:cert-manager/page] cert-manager can obtain certificates from a variety of certificate authorities, including: Let's Encrypt, HashiCorp Vault, CyberArk Certificate Manager and private PKI.
[src:cert-manager/page] With cert-manager's Certificate resource, the private key and certificate are stored in a Kubernetes Secret which is mounted by an application Pod or used by an Ingress controller.
[src:cert-manager/page] With csi-driver, csi-driver-spiffe, or istio-csr , the private key is generated on-demand, before the application starts up; the private key never leaves the node and it is not stored in a Kubernetes Secret.
[src:cert-manager/page] This website provides the full technical documentation for the project, and can be used as a reference; if you feel that there's anything missing, please let us know or raise a PR to add it.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] A **public key infrastructure** (**PKI**) is a set of roles, policies, hardware, software and procedures used to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key cryptography set-ups.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] In cryptography, a PKI is an arrangement that *binds* public keys with respective identities of entities (like people and organizations).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The binding is established through a process of registration and issuance of certificates at and by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Depending on the assurance level of the binding, this may be carried out by an automated process or under human supervision.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] When done over a network, this requires using a secure certificate enrollment or certificate management protocol such as CMP.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI role that may be delegated by a CA to assure valid and correct registration is called a *registration authority* (RA).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] An RA is responsible for accepting requests for digital certificates and authenticating the entity making the request.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] RAs, however, do not sign or issue certificates (i.e., an RA is delegated certain tasks on behalf of a CA)." While Microsoft may have referred to a subordinate CA as an RA, this is incorrect according to the X.509 PKI standards.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] RAs do not have the signing authority of a CA and only manage the vetting and provisioning of certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] In the case of Microsoft Standalone CAs, the function of RA does not exist since all of the procedures controlling the CA are based on the administration and access procedure associated with the system hosting the CA and the CA itself rather than Active Directory.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Most non-Microsoft commercial PKI solutions offer a stand-alone RA component.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] An entity must be uniquely identifiable within each CA domain on the basis of information about that entity.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] A third-party validation authority (VA) can provide this entity information on behalf of the CA.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] PKI provides "trust services" - in plain terms trusting the actions or outputs of entities, be they people or computers.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Trust service objectives respect one or more of the following capabilities: Confidentiality, Integrity and Authenticity (CIA).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Public-key cryptography is a cryptographic technique that enables entities to securely communicate on an insecure public network, and reliably verify the identity of an entity via digital signatures.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] A public key infrastructure (PKI) is a system for the creation, storage, and distribution of digital certificates, which are used to verify that a particular public key belongs to a certain entity.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI creates digital certificates that map public keys to entities, securely stores these certificates in a central repository and revokes them if needed.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The primary role of the CA is to digitally sign and publish the public key bound to a given user.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This is done using the CA's own private key, so that trust in the user key relies on one's trust in the validity of the CA's key.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] When the CA is a third party separate from the user and the system, then it is called the Registration Authority (RA), which may or may not be separate from the CA.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The key-to-user binding is established, depending on the level of assurance the binding has, by software or under human supervision.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The term trusted third party (TTP) may also be used for certificate authority (CA).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Moreover, PKI is itself often used as a synonym for a CA implementation.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or mis-issued certificate until expiry.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] In this model of trust relationships, a CA is a trusted third party – trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Following major issues in how certificate issuing was managed, all major players gradually distrusted Symantec-issued certificates, starting in 2017 and completed in 2021.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This approach involves a server that acts as an offline certificate authority within a single sign-on system.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] A single sign-on server will issue digital certificates into the client system, but never stores them.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Users can execute programs, etc. with the temporary certificate.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] It is common to find this solution variety with X.509-based certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Starting Sep 2020, TLS Certificate Validity reduced to 13 Months.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] An alternative approach to the problem of public authentication of public key information is the web-of-trust scheme, which uses self-signed certificates and third-party attestations of those certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The singular term "web of trust" does not imply the existence of a single web of trust, or common point of trust, but rather one of any number of potentially disjoint "webs of trust".
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Examples of implementations of this approach are PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) and GnuPG (an implementation of OpenPGP, the standardized specification of PGP).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Because PGP and implementations allow the use of e-mail digital signatures for self-publication of public key information, it is relatively easy to implement one's own web of trust.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] One of the benefits of the web of trust, such as in PGP, is that it can interoperate with a PKI CA fully trusted by all parties in a domain (such as an internal CA in a company) that is willing to guarantee certificates, as a trusted introducer.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] If the "web of trust" is completely trusted then, because of the nature of a web of trust, trusting one certificate is granting trust to all the certificates in that web.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI is only as valuable as the standards and practices that control the issuance of certificates and including PGP or a personally instituted web of trust could significantly degrade the trustworthiness of that enterprise's or domain's implementation of PKI.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Another alternative, which does not deal with public authentication of public key information, is the simple public key infrastructure (SPKI), which grew out of three independent efforts to overcome the complexities of X.509 and PGP's web of trust.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not associate users with persons, since the *key* is what is trusted, rather than the person.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not use any notion of trust, as the verifier is also the issuer.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This is called an "authorization loop" in SPKI terminology, where authorization is integral to its design.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This type of PKI is specially useful for making integrations of PKI that do not rely on third parties for certificate authorization, certificate information, etc.; a good example of this is an air-gapped network in an office.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Decentralized identifiers (DIDs) eliminate dependence on centralized registries for identifiers as well as centralized certificate authorities for key management, which is the standard in hierarchical PKI.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] In cases where the DID registry is a distributed ledger, each entity can serve as its own root authority.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This architecture is referred to as decentralized PKI (DPKI).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Developments in PKI occurred in the early 1970s at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, where James Ellis, Clifford Cocks and others made important discoveries related to encryption algorithms and key distribution.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Because developments at GCHQ are highly classified, the results of this work were kept secret and not publicly acknowledged until the mid-1990s.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The public disclosure of both secure key exchange and asymmetric key algorithms in 1976 by Diffie, Hellman, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman changed secure communications entirely.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Assorted cryptographic protocols were invented and analyzed within which the new cryptographic primitives could be effectively used.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] With the invention of the World Wide Web and its rapid spread, the need for authentication and secure communication became still more acute.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Commercial reasons alone (e.g., e-commerce, online access to proprietary databases from web browsers) were sufficient.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Taher Elgamal and others at Netscape developed the SSL protocol ('https' in Web URLs); it included key establishment, server authentication (prior to v3, one-way only), and so on.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI structure was thus created for Web users/sites wishing secure communications.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Vendors and entrepreneurs saw the possibility of a large market, started companies (or new projects at existing companies), and began to agitate for legal recognition and protection from liability.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Consumer groups raised questions about privacy, access, and liability considerations, which were more taken into consideration in some jurisdictions than in others.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The enacted laws and regulations differed, and there were technical and operational problems in converting PKI schemes into successful commercial operation.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Progress has been much slower than pioneers had imagined it would be.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] By the first few years of the 21st century, the underlying cryptographic engineering was clearly not easy to deploy correctly.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Operating procedures (manual or automatic) were not easy to correctly design (nor even if so designed, to execute perfectly, which the engineering required).
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] The standards that existed were insufficient.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] PKI vendors have found a market, but it is not quite the market envisioned in the mid-1990s, and it has grown both more slowly and in somewhat different ways than were anticipated.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] PKIs have not solved some of the problems they were expected to, and several major vendors have gone out of business or been acquired by others.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] PKI has had the most success in government implementations; the largest PKI implementation to date is the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) PKI infrastructure for the Common Access Cards program.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Some argue that purchasing certificates for securing websites by SSL/TLS and securing software by code signing is a costly venture for small businesses.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] However, the emergence of free alternatives, such as Let's Encrypt, has changed this.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] HTTP/2, the latest version of HTTP protocol, allows unsecured connections in theory; in practice, major browser companies have made it clear that they would support this protocol only over a PKI secured TLS connection.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Web browser implementation of HTTP/2 including Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Edge supports HTTP/2 only over TLS by using the ALPN extension of the TLS protocol.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This would mean that, to get the speed benefits of HTTP/2, website owners would be forced to purchase SSL/TLS certificates controlled by corporations.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Currently the majority of web browsers are shipped with pre-installed intermediate certificates issued and signed by a certificate authority, by public keys certified by so-called root certificates.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] This means browsers need to carry a large number of different certificate providers, increasing the risk of a key compromise.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] When a key is known to be compromised, it could be fixed by revoking the certificate, but such a compromise is not easily detectable and can be a huge security breach.
[src:cert-manager/public-key-infrastructure] Browsers have to issue a security patch to revoke intermediary certificates issued by a compromised root certificate authority.
